1230","Abt 1225":"about 1225","Abt 1207":"about 1207","Abt 1228":"about 1228","1207":"1207","Freguesia de Numão, Concelho de Vila Nova de Foz Côa, Distrito da Guarda, Portugal":"Guarda, Portugal","Of,,, Portugal":"Portugal","Portugal":"Portugal","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Suarez","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Carlos, Manuel, Luis, Jorge, Miguel, Jesus, Mario, Roberto, Pedro, Raul.","Spanish (<b>Suárez</b>): patronymic from the medieval personal name   Suero  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Suares","meanings":["Spanish: variant of   Suarez  ."]},{"name":"Suero","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Manuel, Fernando, Ramon, Ana, Jesus, Jorge, Julio, Luis, Orlando, Rafael.","Spanish: from the medieval personal name <i>Suero</i>, from Latin <i>Suarius</i>, from <i>suarius</i> ‘swineherd’, a typical <i>nomen humilitatis</i> (‘name as a sign of humility’) of the early Christian times."]}]},{"name":"Gallego","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Carlos, Luis, Jesus, Julio, Enrique, Guillermo, Jorge, Luz, Manuel, Alvaro.","Spanish: usually an ethnic name for someone from Galicia, Spanish <i>gallego</i>, but perhaps occasionally a nickname from <i>gallego</i>, a word of several meanings including ‘north-west wind’, ‘simple-minded’, ‘deaf-mute’, and a variety of bird."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mayor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Pedro, Agapito, Alberto, Cesar, Cosme, Javier, Jorge, Jose, Juan, Manuel, Orlando.","English (Lancashire): variant of   Mayer   1.","Spanish: nickname for an older man or a distinguishing epithet for the elder of two bearers of the same personal name, from <i>may